comments.body:
@MastermindPanda you shouldn't need admin perms to create a named pipe. After starting and you receive that error do you still see the pipe with the following powershell command?:

`dir \\.\pipe\ | Where-Object Name -Match docker_engine`

When the pipe is created it grants full access to the system as well as your user, so your user should be able to access and connect to it (unless some sort of group policy or other restriction is somehow preventing them). The element that is generating the failure is on the connection side though, however there is a short lived polling action, so I am just curious if it exists and is spurious.

@MastermindPanda thanks for checking!

Could you also try running the following as a powershell script (for admin and not admin) after making sure podman is shutdown (podman machine stop)? I am curious how long of a delay you are seeing, and if there is a variations between admin and not admin. Thanks!

```powershell
podman machine start
Write-Host "Waiting for docker_engine..."
Measure-Command {
$sock = "\\.\pipe\docker_engine"
$exists = test-path  $sock
while (!$exists) {
   $exists = test-path $sock
   Start-Sleep -Milliseconds 100
}
Write-Host "Found docker_engine!"
}
podman machine stop
```
